# Newsletter Reader вЂ” Python + Flask App

A local-first newsletter aggregator that pulls emails from **Apple Mail** (AppleScript) and **Gmail** (Gmail API), stores them in **SQLite**, and uses the **Gemini API** to auto-detect newsletter senders.

---

## Background & Goals

| Goal | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Dual source** | Read from Apple Mail (macOS only, via AppleScript) and Gmail (cross-platform, via Gmail API) |
| **Offline-first** | Full email content stored locally in SQLite вЂ” app works entirely offline after sync |
| **AI-powered detection** | On first run, scan the inbox and use Gemini to classify which senders are newsletters |
| **Clean web UI** | Inbox list view + full reading view, sync button, responsive design |
| **Free APIs only** | Gmail API (free), Gemini API free tier, no paid services |

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **macOS Permissions**: The Apple Mail integration requires granting **Automation** permission to Terminal (or whichever app runs the Flask server) in **System Settings в†’ Privacy & Security в†’ Automation**. The user will be prompted on first run.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Gmail OAuth Setup**: The user must create a Google Cloud project, enable the Gmail API, configure an OAuth consent screen, and download `credentials.json` before Gmail sync will work. The plan includes a setup guide in the README.

> [!WARNING]
> **Gemini API Free Tier**: Inputs/outputs on the free tier may be used by Google to improve their products. The free tier has rate limits (~15 RPM, ~1500 RPD). Newsletter detection for a large inbox may need batching.

---

## Open Questions

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Scope of inbox scan**: Should the initial scan pull the last N emails (e.g., 500) or attempt the entire inbox? A large inbox could take significant time and hit Gemini rate limits. **Recommendation: default to last 500, configurable.**

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Apple Mail accounts**: Should the app scan all accounts configured in Apple Mail, or just a specific one? **Recommendation: scan all accounts by default, let the user filter later.**

> [!NOTE]
> **Image proxying**: Newsletter HTML often contains remote images. Should these be cached locally during sync for true offline viewing, or left as remote URLs? Caching adds complexity and storage. **Recommendation: leave as remote URLs for v1, add caching as a future enhancement.**

---

## Architecture Overview

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Data Sources"
        AM["Apple Mail<br/>(AppleScript via subprocess)"]
        GM["Gmail<br/>(Gmail API + OAuth2)"]
    end

    subgraph "Backend (Flask)"
        SYNC["Sync Engine"]
        AI["Gemini AI<br/>Newsletter Detector"]
        DB[(SQLite Database)]
        API["Flask Routes<br/>(HTML + JSON API)"]
    end

    subgraph "Frontend (Jinja2 + Vanilla JS/CSS)"
        INBOX["Inbox View"]
        READ["Reading View"]
        SETTINGS["Settings / Sync"]
    end

    AM -->|"subprocess + osascript"| SYNC
    GM -->|"google-api-python-client"| SYNC
    SYNC --> DB
    DB --> API
    AI -->|"classify senders"| DB
    API --> INBOX
    API --> READ
    API --> SETTINGS
```

